"Douvris C., Ozerov O.V.","Hydrodefluorination of perfluoroalkyl groups using silylium-carborane catalysts",2008,"Science","321","5893",,"1188","1190",,,10.1126/science.1159979,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-50649087926&partnerID=40&md5=56e690febdb2906892b0df31981a907e","Department of Chemistry, Brandeis University, MS 015, 415 South Street, Waltham, MA 02454, United States","Douvris, C., Department of Chemistry, Brandeis University, MS 015, 415 South Street, Waltham, MA 02454, United States; Ozerov, O.V., Department of Chemistry, Brandeis University, MS 015, 415 South Street, Waltham, MA 02454, United States","Carbon-fluorine bonds are among the most unreactive functionalities in chemistry. Interest in their activation arises in part from the high global warming potentials of anthropogenic polyfluoroorganic compounds. Conversion to carbon-hydrogen bonds (hydrodefluorination) is the simplest modification of carbon-fluorine bonds, but efficient catalytic hydrodefluorination of perfluoroalkyl groups has been an unmet challenge. We report a class of carborane-supported, highly electrophilic silylium compounds that act as long-lived catalysts for hydrodefluorination of trifluoromethyl and nonafluorobutyl groups by widely accessible silanes under mild conditions. The reactions are completely selective for aliphatic carbon-fluorine bonds in preference to aromatic carbon-fluorine bonds.",,"carbon; carborane derivative; fluorine; hydrogen; silane derivative; catalysis; fluorine; global warming; warming; article; catalyst; chemical bond; chemical modification; chemical reaction; fluorination; priority journal",,"carbon, 7440-44-0; fluorine, 7782-41-4; hydrogen, 12385-13-6, 1333-74-0",,,,"Hiyama, T., (2000) Organofluorine Compounds: Chemistry and Applications, , Springer, New York; Kiplinger, J.L., Richmond, T.G., Osterberg, C.E., (1994) Chem. Rev, 94, p. 373; Burdeniuc, J., Jedlicka, B., Crabtree, R.H., (1997) Chem. Ber, 130, p. 145; Richmond, T.G., (1999) Topics in Organometallic Chemistry, 3, pp. 243-269. , S. Murai, Ed, Springer, New York; Braun, T., Perutz, R.N., (2007) Comprehensive Organometallic Chemistry III, 1. , R. H. Crabtree, D. M. P. Mingos, Eds, Elsevier, Oxford, chap. 26; (2004) Handbook of Fluorous Chemistry, , J. A. Gladysz, D. P. Curran, I. T. Horvath, Eds, Wiley-VCH, Weinheim, Germany; Ochoa-Herrera, V., (2008) Environ. Sci. Technol, 42, p. 3260; Shine, K.P., Sturges, W.T., (2007) Science, 315, p. 1804; Chakrabarti, N., Jacobus, J., (1988) Macromolecules, 21, p. 3011; Terao, J., (2007) Chem. Commun, 2007, p. 855; Fuchibe, K., Akiyama, T., (2006) J. Am. Chem. Soc, 128, p. 1434; Le Fave, G.M., (1949) J. Am. Chem. Soc, 71, p. 4148; White Jr., L., Rice, O.K., (1947) J. Am. Chem. Soc, 69, p. 267; Scott, V.J., Çelenligil-Çetin, R., Ozerov, O.V., (2005) J. Am. Chem. Soc, 127, p. 2852; Using textbook bond energy values from 31Krause, J.R., Lampe, F.W., (1977) J. Phys. Chem, 81, p. 281; , 33. , For an overview of gas-phase C-F activation, seeLambert, J.B., Zhang, S., (1993) J. Chem. Soc. Chem. Commun, 1993, p. 383; Panisch, R., Bolte, M., Mueller, T., (2006) J. Am. Chem. Soc, 128, p. 9676; Klahn, M., Fischer, C., Spannenberg, A., Rosenthal, U., Krossing, I., (2007) Tet. Lett, 48, p. 8900; Korbe, S., Schreiber, P.J., Michl, J., (2006) Chem. Rev, 106, p. 5208; Reed, C.A., (2005) Chem. Commun, 2005, p. 1669; Reed, C.A., (1998) Acc. Chem. Res, 31, p. 133; Reed, C.A., (1998) Acc. Chem. Res, 31, p. 325; Juhasz, M., Hoffmann, S., Stoyanov, E., Kim, K., Reed, C.A., (2004) Angew. Chem. Int. Ed, 43, p. 5352; Materials and methods are available as supporting material on Science OnlineAizenberg, M., Milstein, D., (1994) Science, 265, p. 359; Reed, C.A., (2003) J. Am. Chem. Soc, 125, p. 1796; Curiously, in the polymerization of cyclo-[NPCl2] 3 by R3Si[carborane], a similar discrepancy between lower coordinating ability and higher activity was reported (32)Stevenson, D.P., Morgan, J.H., (1948) J. Am. Chem. Soc, 70, p. 